The suppression of the virus has resulted in the development of so-called resistant viruses on which drugs are more effective.
The work of the experts from the three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠcht Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with the resistance to the virus.
They have shown that substances called Metalocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
The Metalokarborane are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way of all drugs used today, and therefore they can overcome the problem of resistance.
In his work, the scientists to new ´ improved ’ compounds, prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their attachment to the viral protein.
The Metalokarborane have a unique three-dimensional structure: two cages poliedros composed of atoms of boron, hydrogen and carbon atom are linked by a metal atom, in this case the Cobalt.
A traitor and resilient virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the Division of HIV protease caused by the HIV virus would be no mature infectious particles of the virus.
If we stop HIV protease, we stop the spread of the virus in the body of the patient, explain the scientists in a press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In the work published in the scientific journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic link, which is then systematically amended.
A little weaker, but more reliable.
The effect of this series of substances against the HIV protease was tested in test, and also against their variants resistant, obtained from patients infected with HIV.
The effect of the variant of the enzyme is not as strong as in the clinically used drugs, but they do not lose their effect on the resistant variants against which the drugs are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action and their other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical changes are therefore interesting compounds for further research towards the development of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina Rezacova, head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology of the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
